{"key":"post-8559232","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8559232</id>\n<content>You want to fill your jars loosely, but make sure there's no air pockets created as you load.&amp;nbsp; If you're not careful, a 'clump' might cause the area around and under it not to fill, and then it comes apart and settles during sterilization.&amp;nbsp; Don't pack, but it doesn't hurt to slap the side of the jar a time or two as you fill, and especially after topping with dry verm.&amp;nbsp; Tap the side of the jar with a wooden spoon or something, and then replace any verm that settles.&amp;nbsp; If using upside down lids, you can actually fill the verm a little bit above the edge of the jar and it fits into the divot on the lid.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;At this point, since your verm barrier might have slipped down the sides, I'd suggest covering the 4 holes with micropore medical tape, and then sticking another piece right over the first one after you inoculate.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8559247</next>\n<prev>8559206</prev>\n<first>8558935</first>\n<last>8559247</last>\n<when>1214349903</when>\n<utime>06/25/08 02:25 AM</utime>\n</post>"}